\begin_layout Standard
On July 12, 2016, University of Guam research assistant Christopher Rosario
 discovered a colony of large wasps nesting in a hollow avocado tree in
 Dededo, Guam (13.50533ยบ N, 144.80134ยบ E).
 The wasps were aggressive, resulting in only a single specimen being collected.
 This observation was posted on the iNaturalist web site (
\begin_inset Flex Flex:URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/3663868
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On July 20, 2016, Arnold Perez of the Leo Palace Resort delivered 5 specimens
 of 
\shape italic
Vespa tropica
\shape default
 to Dr.
 Aubrey Moore at the University of Guam.
 Perez discovered a nest near a swiiming pool (
\begin_inset Flex Flex:URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/3710757
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 Specimens were placed in the University of Guam Insect Collection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A press release was issued requesting residents of Guam to report sightings
 of 
\emph on
V.
 tropica
\emph default
.
 These sightings are being documented in an iNaturalist project set up for
 this purpose (
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://www.inaturalist.org/projects/vespa-tropica-on-guam
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Description
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
UOG entomologists (Sablan and Moore) identified the wasp as 
\shape italic
Vespa tropica
\shape default
 based on publicly available images and keys 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "archer1991taxonomy"

\end_inset

.
 This species determination was confirmed by Dr.
 Jason Mottern at the USDA Systematic Entomology Laboratory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Vespa tropica
\emph default
 is a medium-sized to large species.
 Queens reach 30mm or more, males average 26mm and workers average 24 to
 26mm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nest of 
\shape italic
Vespa tropica
\shape default
 is usually underground or in a tree hollow or similar enclosed space.
 Due to the location, the nest is seldom seen.
 If excavated, the nest usually appears rhomboid or bowl-shaped, with an
 open bottom (as opposed to the completely sealed nests of most aerial hornets).
 The nest envelope is laminar (comprising of distinct, broad individual
 layers) and very brittle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Human Health Risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
V.
 tropica
\emph default
 is very aggressive and readily stings in the vicinity of its nest.
 Death caused by the venom from multiple stings from this species has been
 documented, but this is very rare.
 As with any stinging insect, an allergic reaction (anaphylaxis) is far
 more dangerous.
 About 3% of adults are allergic to insect stings 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "golden2007insectsting"

\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Environmental and Agricultural Risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This species is known to attack the nests of Polistines (paper wasps) in
 order to obtain the larvae to feed their own larvae.
 On Guam, a video recording has been made by Wayne Borja which documents
 
\emph on
V.
 tropica
\emph default
 raiding a 
\emph on
Polistes stigma
\emph default
 nest, one of 2 species of small paper wasps locally referred to as ''boonie
 bees'' (
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gVXR44ixrxk
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 
\emph on
V.
 tropica
\emph default
 has also been reported to raid hives of the European honeybee, 
\emph on
Apis mellifera
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "burgett1982predation"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

